We will begin by splitting our data into training and testing sets, using a 20% test size:

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

2.1   Models¶

2.1.1   Random Forest¶

We will create a Random Forest classifier and experiment with different values for n_estimators, max_depth, and criterion using GridSearchCV:

In [ ]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# set parameters
n_estimators = [5, 10, 50, 100, 500]
max_depth = [1, 2, 4, 5, 10, 20, 50]
rfc_params = dict(n_estimators=n_estimators, max_depth=max_depth)

# create classifiers
rfc_gini    = RandomForestClassifier(criterion='gini'   , random_state=42)
rfc_entropy = RandomForestClassifier(criterion='entropy', random_state=42)

# create grids
rfc_gini_grid    = GridSearchCV(rfc_gini   , rfc_params, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
rfc_entropy_grid = GridSearchCV(rfc_entropy, rfc_params, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')

# fit grids
rfc_gini_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
rfc_entropy_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

# print basic results
print(f'Gini Best Params: {rfc_gini_grid.best_params_} Score: {rfc_gini_grid.best_score_}')
print(f'Entropy Best Params: {rfc_entropy_grid.best_params_} Score: {rfc_entropy_grid.best_score_}')

# create dataframe from cv_results_
rfc_gini_results = pd.DataFrame(rfc_gini_grid.cv_results_)
rfc_entropy_results = pd.DataFrame(rfc_entropy_grid.cv_results_)

# pivot as prep for heatmap
rfc_gini_pivot = rfc_gini_results.pivot_table(index='param_n_estimators', columns='param_max_depth', values='mean_test_score')
rfc_entropy_pivot = rfc_entropy_results.pivot_table(index='param_n_estimators', columns='param_max_depth', values='mean_test_score')

# heatmap to visualize results
fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 3))
sns.heatmap(rfc_gini_pivot, annot=True, cmap='YlGnBu', fmt='.4f', ax=ax1[0], cbar=False)
ax1[0].set_title('Heatmap of mean test score (Gini)')
sns.heatmap(rfc_entropy_pivot, annot=True, cmap='YlGnBu', fmt='.4f', ax=ax1[1])
ax1[1].set_title('Heatmap of mean test score (Entropy)')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Gini Best Params: {'max_depth': 10, 'n_estimators': 500} Score: 0.9316993464052288
Entropy Best Params: {'max_depth': 10, 'n_estimators': 500} Score: 0.9313725490196079

We can see for both gini and entropy criterion, as both max_depth and n_estimators increase, the accuracy score increases as well. This is expected. However, we must not take too large of a value for these parameters, especially for max_depth, as this will lead to overfitting. We will use max_depth=10, n_estimators=500 and criterion=gini for our random forest model. This was determined through the grid search as a good balance between accuracy and overfitting. It reduces our parameter values as much as possible while still maintaining a high accuracy score. Note though that we have still not tested this on unseen data, our testing set. This will be done later and a better idea of the model's true performance will be known.

2.1.2   Bagging¶

We will create a Bagging classifier and experiment with different values for n_estimators using GridSearchCV:

In [ ]:
from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier

# set parameters
n_estimators = [5, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 100, 500]
bag_params = dict(n_estimators=n_estimators)

# create classifier
bag = BaggingClassifier(random_state=42)

# create grid
bag_grid = GridSearchCV(bag, bag_params, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')

# fit grid
bag_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

# print basic results
print(f'Best Params: {bag_grid.best_params_} Score: {bag_grid.best_score_}')

# create dataframe from cv_results_
bag_results = pd.DataFrame(bag_grid.cv_results_)

# pivot as prep for heatmap
bag_pivot = bag_results.pivot_table(index='param_n_estimators', values='mean_test_score')

# heatmap to visualize results
fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots(figsize=(3, 3))
sns.heatmap(bag_pivot, annot=True, cmap='YlGnBu', fmt='.4f', ax=ax2)
ax2.set_title('Heatmap of mean test score')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Best Params: {'n_estimators': 10} Score: 0.9088235294117648

In the Bagging Classifier, we can see that as n_estimators increases, the score actually does not continuously increase. It reaches a maximum, for at least options we provided, at 10. A lower number of estimators is also less prone to overfitting. We will use n_estimators=10 for our bagging model.

2.1.3   AdaBoost¶

We will create an AdaBoost classifier and experiment with different values for n_estimators and learning_rate using GridSearchCV:

In [ ]:
from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostClassifier

# set parameters
n_estimators = [5, 10, 50, 100, 500]
learning_rate = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1.0]
ada_params = dict(n_estimators=n_estimators, learning_rate=learning_rate)

# create classifier
ada = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=42)

# create grid
ada_grid = GridSearchCV(ada, ada_params, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')

# fit grid
ada_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

# print basic results
print(f'Best Params: {ada_grid.best_params_} Score: {ada_grid.best_score_}')

# create dataframe from cv_results_
ada_results = pd.DataFrame(ada_grid.cv_results_)

# pivot as prep for heatmap
ada_pivot = ada_results.pivot_table(index='param_n_estimators', columns='param_learning_rate', values='mean_test_score')

# heatmap to visualize results
fig3, ax3 = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 3))
sns.heatmap(ada_pivot, annot=True, cmap='YlGnBu', fmt='.4f', ax=ax3)
ax3.set_title('Heatmap of mean test score')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Best Params: {'learning_rate': 0.001, 'n_estimators': 500} Score: 0.669281045751634

In the AdaBoost Classifier we can see that as n_estimators increases and learning_rate decreases, the score increases. However, at least in our dataset there seems to be a near repeat of the highest score lower in the parameter range. To attempt to prevent overfitting, we will not use use the best parameters as determined by the grid search but instead n_estimators=50 and learning_rate=0.01 for our AdaBoost model as seen from our score heatmap.

The accuracies of each model we created on the testing set can be seen from the table, confusion matricies, and classification reports above. Random Forest, Bagging, and Gradient Boosting classifiers all have identical accuracies (at least up to 6 decimal places as seen in the 2.1.1 Accuracies table). We provided different parameters for each model, but as our selections were specific to each model we seemed to have gotten the best results we could out of each of these for the training data, thus arriving at a similar (in this case almost exact) accuracy for the testing set. AdaBoost has a much lower accuracy. This is most likely attributed to the model not being the right fit for our dataset rather than improper parameter selection. However, it is a simple 1 level decison tree model so perhaps with many more n_estimators than other models it can perform at an accuracy that is on par with the other models. We will not explore this further though.

3   Random Forests vs Decision Tree Classifiers¶

In this section we will compare a random forest with two simple decision trees. Additionally, we will determine the optimal number of trees in the forest for optimal performance in terms of accuracy, using a cross validation technique.

Note that in section 2 we were tuning hyper parameters and chosing a model afterwards, so we did our cross validation via a grid search on our training data only, leaving some data as unseen for testing. In this section, we will be using cross validation on our entire dataset, including our testing data. We are not making a model later, but instead simply determining the optimal number of trees in the random forest. Here we will be using the cross_val_score function from sklearn to do this.

2 simple Decision Tree Classifiers and their accuracies under 10 fold cross validation:

In [ ]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

# create two simple decision tree classifiers, one with max_depth=1 and one with max_depth=3
dtc_max1 = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=1, random_state=42)
dtc_max3 = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, random_state=42)


from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# use cross_val_score to get the mean accuracy score for each classifier
dtc_max1_scores = cross_val_score(dtc_max1, X, y, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
dtc_max1_score = dtc_max1_scores.mean()
print(f"Accuracy for dtc_max1: {dtc_max1_score}")

dtc_max3_scores = cross_val_score(dtc_max3, X, y, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
dtc_max3_score = dtc_max3_scores.mean()
print(f"Accuracy for dtc_max3: {dtc_max3_score}")

Accuracy for dtc_max1: 0.4383116883116883
Accuracy for dtc_max3: 0.7852813852813852

100 Random Forest Classifiers and their accuracies under 10 fold cross validation:

In [ ]:
# 100 random forest models with increasing number of decision trees

# list to store the classifiers
rfc_clfs = []

# list to store the number of decision trees
n_trees = list(range(1, 101))

for i in n_trees:
    # create classifier
    rfc_i = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=i, max_depth=3, random_state=42)
    
    # fit classifier
    rfc_i.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # store classifier
    rfc_clfs.append(rfc_i)

# list to store cv scores
rfc_cv_scores = []

# loop over the classifiers
for rfc_clf in rfc_clfs:
    # compute cv score
    score = cross_val_score(rfc_clf, X, y, cv=10)
    
    # store mean
    rfc_cv_scores.append(score.mean())

# print scores (commened out as output can be simplified via graph as seen in cell below)
# for i, cv_score in enumerate(rfc_cv_scores, 1):
#     print(f"Accuracy for {i} estimators: {cv_score}")
In [ ]:
import numpy as np

# highest score and its respective number of decision trees
rfc_highest_score = np.max(rfc_cv_scores)
rfc_optimal_trees = np.argmax(rfc_cv_scores) + 1

The random forest model has a much greater accuracy than the simple decision tree model (88.1% peak at 30 trees vs 78.5% respectively). This is expected as the random forest model is an ensemble of decision trees.

(219,)

Now, for each of the 5 target classes, we will create an ROC curve for each of the 5 models.
This will result in 25 ROC curves.
They will first be presented as a plot for each Classifier Model, with the 5 curves of same model type from different classes on each plot. (Along with mean roc_auc score printed for each model.)
They will then be presented as a plot for each weld defect type, with 5 curves of same defect type from different models on each plot. (Along with mean roc_auc score printed for each weld defect type.)
This allows data visualization and observation in either way, depending on what is being looked for.
Also note that as we are doing cross validation, we are using the entire dataset, not split into testing and training manually.

In [ ]:
fig7, axs = plt.subplots(len(models), 1, figsize=(8,4*len(models)))

for i, (model, ax) in enumerate(zip(models, axs)):

    roc_auc_score_vars = []
    cv_scores_vars = []
    for j in range(n_classes):
        cv_prob_true = {}
        cv_probs = cross_val_predict(model, X, y_bin[:,j], cv=folds, method='predict_proba')
        cv_prob_true = cv_probs[:,1]
        fpr, tpr, thresh = roc_curve(y_bin[:,j], cv_prob_true)

        roc_auc_score_var = roc_auc_score(y_bin[:,j], cv_prob_true)
        roc_auc_score_vars.append(roc_auc_score_var)

        cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X, y_bin[:,j], cv=folds, scoring='accuracy')
        cv_mean = cv_scores.mean()
        cv_scores_vars.append(cv_mean)

        ax.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f'{types[j]} | roc_auc: {roc_auc_score_var:.4f} | cv_mean: {cv_mean:.4f}')

    print(f'{model.__class__.__name__} | mean roc_auc: {np.mean(roc_auc_score_vars):.4f}')
    print(f'{model.__class__.__name__} | mean cv_mean: {np.mean(cv_scores_vars):.4f}')

    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', color='gray', label='base 0.5')
    ax.set_title(f'ROC Curves - Model: {model.__class__.__name__}')
    ax.set_xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    ax.set_ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    ax.legend(loc='lower right')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observing the ROC curves, a few different things can be seen, and multiple conclusions can be made.

  • In regards to model type, Random Forest has the highest mean roc_auc score at 0.9885 (printed just before the first ROC plot). This is followed by Gradient Boosting and Bagging both at ~0.973. AdaBoost and KNN trail behind. This is expected as Random Forest is an ensemble method, and Gradient Boosting and Bagging are both based on decision trees. AdaBoost is also an ensemble method, but it is a weak learner based on decision stumps (1 level decision trees), which are much simpler than full decision trees of course. It would need many more trees to possibly get near the accuracies of our other models. KNN is also a simpler model, and has a lower roc_auc score. The mean cv_mean is also highest in the Random Forest Classifier. If we had to only chose 1 model as our optimal model, this would be it.
  • In regards to weld defect type, CR has the highest mean roc_auc score at 0.9926 and mean cv_mean score at 0.9741. However, we can also see that weld defect type PO has high scores as well; 0.9887 mean roc_auc and 0.9718 mean cv_mean. If we look at the PO plot we can see that for all models but the KNN model, the lines stick to near perfect. If the KNN model was not included in these PO scores, it may be the highest scored defect type. Also note from the last plot we can see SL is the hardest to classify for any model.

Overall, we must remember the final ultimate goal is to classify the weld defect types absoutely. This is likely the primacy concern of the end customer. Thus, for some weld defect types, our one chosen optimal Random Forest model may not be the best. We can use it for its LF, PO, and SL type detetions as its roc_auc scores for those types are the highest out of all the models, but for CR and LP, the KNN model actually does slightly better. In this model, the differences betwene these roc_auc scores are very small and not worth the tradeoff to use a different model for some other types and introducing a higher level of complexity into the system. However, on other datesets and problems, there may be much larger differences, thus this is something to keep in mind.

In conclusion, it is important to remmeber goals when creating models. Do we want to get the highest accuracy or the fastest runtime or simplest method? The data can then be thoroughly explored with those goals in mind, and muliple models created and used in conjunction if necessary.
